## Problem

Spec mu-026-bash-tool B-7 asserts: "bash(\"yes\") (would produce infinite output) — capped at 64KB, result includes truncation marker. is_error may be true (timeout) or false (the cap was hit and we killed the process) — both acceptable."

The cap behavior is real (verified in code: truncate_to_cap in crates/mu-coding/src/tools/bash.rs), and the helper unit test truncate_to_cap_respects_utf8_boundary covers the truncation function in isolation. But there's no integration test that exercises the full B-7 path: spawn a stream-heavy command → cap kicks in → result includes truncation marker.

## Why this matters

Surfaced 2026-05-16 during mu-026 spec-vs-impl sync. Missing test means a regression that broke the cap (e.g. a refactor of the wait loop that mishandled the timeout-vs-cap race) wouldn't be caught.

## Scope

Add to crates/mu-coding/src/tools/bash.rs#tests:

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn b7_strict_output_cap() {
    let mode = BashMode::strict_with_extras(&["yes".to_string()], false);
    // 'yes' runs forever; either timeout or output-cap will terminate.
    let result = execute_bash(mode, json!({ "command": "yes", "timeout_secs": 5 })).await;
    // Either path is acceptable per spec:
    // - timeout fires first → is_error: true, message says 'timed out'
    // - output cap fires first → result contains truncation marker
    let timed_out = result.content.contains("timed out");
    let truncated = result.content.contains("truncated");
    assert!(timed_out || truncated, "expected timeout or truncation marker, got: {}", result.content);
}
```

Also worth: a deterministic variant that doesn't rely on race timing — pipe known-size output to head/dd via yolo mode, verify exact cap behavior.

## Acceptance

- New test b7_strict_output_cap in bash.rs (or a more deterministic variant)
- cargo test --workspace passes
- Spec mu-026 B-7 line gets the corresponding test name reference

